<h3>A Great Idea is a Combination of Two Good Ideas</h3>

<p>I&#39;ve heard multiple versions of this, from&nbsp;<a href="http://scottberkun.com/2011/ideas-are-made-of-other-ideas/" target="_blank">Scott Berkun</a>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<a href="http://www-ui.is.s.u-tokyo.ac.jp/~takeo/" target="_blank">Takeo Igarashi</a>. Project Duet echoes this notion: the combination of smart phone and smart watch yields a set of interaction possibilities much richer than the sum of the two devices alone. My favorite example of this is using the watch to sense which hand part touches the phone: it is finger pad when the watch is facing upwards, side of finger if facing sideways, and knuckle if facing down. There are two things to learn from this: First, the combination of two devices makes this sensing problem magnitudes easier than <a href="http://www.qeexo.com/fingersense/" target="_blank">dealing with either of them alone</a>; Second, it uses the watch in a quite unconventional way - you don&#39;t directly interact with it but it nonetheless serves as a necessary component in realizing the hand part sensing technique, which I will discuss below.</p>

