<h3>The Cross-Disciplinary Perspectives</h3>

<p>Thanks to Autodesk Research&#39;s four-month internship program, I had so much time to play with this project that I even dabbled in linguistics and music.</p>

<p>The linguistic perspective is also my favorite part of this project. I accidentally ran into a paper by Jane Falk entitled &#39;<a href="http://journals.linguisticsociety.org/proceedings/index.php/BLS/article/download/2129/1901" target="_blank">The conversational duet</a>&#39; published in 1980. The nice thing about it is it sheds light on my project despite years&#39; and discplinaries&#39; gap. In a nutshell, Falk observed a convesational behavior of two persons (e.g., a couple, two close friends): they would talk to a 3rd person or party by taking over or following each other&#39;s sentences; and from the listeners&#39; perspective it would sound like a story told by one single person. Isn&#39;t this what the phone, the watch and all the smart devices should try to achieve? Offering interactions to the users to make them feel they are interacting with one single device.</p>

<p>The musical perspective is also quite related and interesting. I read that musicians perform&nbsp;Jazz will pick up each other&#39;s riffs and accordingly perform their own. Again the main idea is collectively&nbsp;<em>multiple</em>&nbsp;musicians are trying to put on one <em>single</em>&nbsp;show that is coherently enjoyable to the audience.</p>

<p>I think it&#39;s a beauty that a project in HCI is able to find similar ideas in other disciplinaries, and more importantly, get informed and inspired by all this cross-disciplinary work. I hope all my projects could have this experience; unfortunately this doesn&#39;t always happen. Foremost, cross-disciplinary research is hard; and it takes time, patience, and some romantic belief to go on an expeidition into the &#39;wild&#39; without necessarily an assurance that at the end of the day you will find something.</p>
